## <a id="252"></a>v2.5.2

**Release Date:**  December 20, 2018

#### Bindings Use DNS

This release completes the transition from bindings via IP addresses to DNS hostnames. This lays the foundation for coming improvements, and also enables Highly Available Clusters (HA Clusters).

### Features

New features and changes in this release:

#### Highly Available Clusters On-Demand

MySQL for PCF now supports **three deployment topologies**. In addition to Single Node and Leader-Follower, Operators can now offer a Highly Available Cluster service plan. For information on how to configure a HA Cluster plan, see [Configure Service Plans](http://docs.pivotal.io/p-mysql/install-config.html#active) option. For information on availability criteria for each topology, see [Availability Options](http://docs.pivotal.io/p-mysql/availability-options.html).

<p class="note warning"><strong>WARNING! </strong> Highly available clusters are <strong>beta</strong> in v2.5.</p>

While in **beta**, the following limitations exist:
- Operators are required to impose a plan quota that is no more than five instances.
- Restoring from backups is a manual process. For more information, see [Restore an HA Cluster Instance](https://docs.pivotal.io/p-mysql/backup-and-restore.html#runHA).
- No encryption at rest for HA clusters.

**Highly Available Clusters are for Advanced Use Cases Only**

In addition to higher infrastructure cost, Galera clusters introduce some significant limitations that are different from running Single-Node or Leader-Follower MySQL. For more information, see [High Availability Limitations](https://docs.pivotal.io/p-mysql/1-10/index.html#limitations).

Due to these limitations, HA Clusters are **not recommended for sharing between multiple users/applications**. Service instance sharing is **disabled** for HA Clusters. If necessary, you can still share by creating User Provided Service Instances (UPSI). For more information, see [User Provided Service Instances](https://docs.pivotal.io/pivotalcf/devguide/services/user-provided.html).

Choose HA Clusters only when the availability criteria that Leader-Follower provides is not sufficient for your application.

**Features of Highly Available Clusters**

- Highly Available clusters are provisioned on-demand.
- Monitoring, diagnostics, and backups are performed from a **jumpbox VM**. For information on how to configure this VM, see [Configure Service Plans](https://docs.pivotal.io/p-mysql/install-config.html#active).
	- The jumpbox VM runs a replication canary that continuously tests replication health between cluster nodes. For more information, see [Replication Canary](https://docs.pivotal.io/p-mysql/1-10/monitor.html#repcanary).
	- Operators can run diagnostics (e.g., disk usage) on an HA cluster by running the `mysql-diag` script on the jumpbox VM. For more information, see [Running mysql-diag](https://docs.pivotal.io/p-mysql/1-10/mysql-diag.html).
	- Like Single Node and Leader-Follower, configuring automatic backups is required. For information on how to configure automated backups, see [Configure Backups](https://docs.pivotal.io/p-mysql/install-config.html#backups). For how to perform a manual backup and restore, see [Backing Up and Restoring On-Demand MySQL for PCF](https://docs.pivotal.io/p-mysql/2-5/backup-and-restore.html).
- Developers can view a dashboard to see the state of each node in the HA cluster. For more information, see [Monitor Node Health Using the Dashboard](https://docs.pivotal.io/p-mysql/2-5/monitor-health.html#dashboard).
